# **C++ Solution:**
```
**// Using Optimal Greedy Approach...**
class Solution {
public:
    int jump(vector<int>& nums) {
        //Initialize left and right pointers to point to the start and end of a segment...
        //segment refers to the steps a particular index can move...
        //Initialize jumps variable to store the number of jumps made so far which will be the minimum...
        int left = 0, right = 0, jump = 0;
        // While right pointer is not at the end of the list...
        while(right < nums.size() - 1){
            int maxi = 0;
            //Loop through the segment and maximize the reach...
            for(int i = left; i < right + 1; i++)
                maxi = max(maxi, nums[i] + i);
            // Update the pointers...
            // left pointer to be at right + 1...
            left = right + 1;
            // right pointer to be at the maximum reach...
            right = maxi;
            jump += 1;
        }
        return jump;
    }
};
```

# **Java Solution:**
```
**// Using Dynamic Programming Approach...**
class Solution {
    public int jump(int[] nums) {
        //Create an auxiliary array to store minimum jumps needed to reach nums[i] from nums[0].
        int[] jump = new int[nums.length];
        jump[0] = 0;
        //Implement a nested loop to traverse the whole list.
        for (int i = 1; i < nums.length; i++) {
            jump[i] = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
            //traverse the segments and stores the minimum jumps to an index in the auxiliary array.
            for(int j = 0; j < i; j++){
                // Find the minimum number of jumps to reach nums[i] from the start
                // And add this value to the auxiliary array.
                if(i <= nums[j] + j && jump[j] != Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
                    jump[i] = Math.min(jump[i], jump[j] + 1);
                }
            }
        }
        return jump[nums.length - 1];   //Return the minimum number of jumps.
    }
}
```

