# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Go on every step and check for maximum reach.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
If there is only one step then return 1 or if you can not take any step return -1. Initially we will start from index 1, and traverse the array and keep updating the maximum reach and decrease steps.
 1. Suppose you are on index 1 (i.e. nums[1] is equal to 3) so you can take 1/2/3 steps and for every step you take max of reach.
 2. When step==0 i.e. you can not take any more step, so you will increment the jump by 1.
 3. And update step by step=max_reach-1. (simple maths)

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(1)$$
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int jump(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int ans = 1;
        int step = nums[0];
        if(n<=1) return 0; 
        if(step==0) return -1; 
        int max_reach=nums[0];
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            if(i==n-1) return ans;
            max_reach=max(max_reach,i+nums[i]);
            step--;
            if(step==0){
                ans++;
                if(i>= max_reach) return -1;
                step=max_reach-i;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

