solutions.content:
There are a lot of introductions about how Morris Traversal works. It is a beautiful algorithm which takes only O(1) space complexity while still maintaining O(n) time complexity. Here I summarized how Morris Traversal is implemented w.r.t. all three orders. 

**Pre-Order:**
```
def preorderTraversal(self, root: TreeNode) -> List[int]:

	res = []

	while root:
		if root.left:
			temp = root.left
			while temp.right and temp.right != root:
				temp = temp.right
			if not temp.right:
				res.append(root.val) 
				temp.right = root
				root = root.left
			else:
				temp.right = None 
				root = root.right
		else:
			res.append(root.val)
			root = root.right

	return res
```
**In-Order**: 

Compared to Pre-Order implementation, the change is just one line as maked "***"
```
def inorderTraversal(self, root: TreeNode) -> List[int]:

	res = []

	while root:
		if root.left:
			temp = root.left
			while temp.right and temp.right != root:
				temp = temp.right
			if not temp.right:
				temp.right = root
				root = root.left
			else:
				res.append(root.val)    # ***
				temp.right = None
				root = root.right
		else:
			res.append(root.val)
			root = root.right

	return res
```
**Post-Order:**

I saw many implementations for the Post-Order to be very complex and hard to remember. Here I provide a simple version. It is very similar to the pre-order one, except that now we are doing everything reversely. By this I mean we go along the direction of right child and link the leftmost child on the right sub tree to the root. Then we leftappend the val to the result. 

THAT`S IT!!
```
def postorderTraversal(self, root: TreeNode) -> List[int]:

	res = deque()

	while root:
		if root.right:
			temp = root.right
			while temp.left and temp.left != root:
				temp = temp.left
			if not temp.left:
				res.appendleft(root.val)
				temp.left = root
				root = root.right
			else:
				temp.left = None
				root = root.left
		else:
			res.appendleft(root.val)
			root = root.left

	return res
```

