**JAVA SOLUTION USING TWO-POINTERS**

*If-else if statements cover up all possible senarios that we may encounter during iteration. We use Two-Pointers i & j to figure out whether its vowel or not and accordingly do the necessary operations. In some cases the ith character may not be included in the character array hence a check for whether the char[i]=='\u000' is required at the end.*


```
class Solution {
    public String reverseVowels(String s) {
        int n=s.length();
        char []a =new char[n];
        int i=0;int j=n-1;

        if(n==1){return s;}  // if only 1 character present in String

        while(i<j){
            int l=Character.getNumericValue(s.charAt(i)); 
            int r=Character.getNumericValue(s.charAt(j));

            if((l!=10&&l!=14&&l!=18&&l!=24&&l!=30) && (r!=10&&r!=14&&r!=18&&r!=24&&r!=30)){
                a[i]=(char)s.charAt(i);
                ++i;
                 a[j]=(char)s.charAt(j);
                --j;

            }
              else  if((l==10||l==14||l==18||l==24||l==30) && (r==10||r==14||r==18||r==24||r==30)) {
                  a[i]=s.charAt(j);
                  a[j]=s.charAt(i);
                  ++i;--j;
              }

          else  if((l==10||l==14||l==18||l==24||l==30) && (r!=10&&r!=14&&r!=18&&r!=24&&r!=30)){
                a[j]=(char)s.charAt(j);
                --j;
            }
          else  if((l!=10&&l!=14&&l!=18&&l!=24&&l!=30) && (r==10||r==14||r==18||r==24||r==30)){
                a[i]=(char)s.charAt(i);
                ++i;
            }
        }

         if(a[i]=='\u0000') //checking if the i-th character is not null(i.e left out)Example i/p:"axyz" here i will never increment in above loop hence this check is required!
             a[i]=s.charAt(i);       

        return new String(a);
    }
}
```

